.TH ZBASE32 1 "February 2026" "BaseX 0.9.1" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
zbase32 \- compress and encode data to Base32 format
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B zbase32
[\fIOPTION\fR]... [\fIFILE\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B zbase32
compresses data using Zstandard and encodes it to Base32 format (RFC 4648).
Base32 uses only alphanumeric characters (A\-Z, 2\-7), making it safe for
case\-insensitive systems and URLs.
.PP
With no FILE, or when FILE is \-, read standard input.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-d ", " \-\-decode
Decode and decompress data (reverses the encoding + compression).
.TP
.BR \-w ", " \-\-wrap=\fICOLS\fR
Wrap encoded lines after COLS characters (default 76). Use 0 for no wrapping.
.TP
.BR \-i ", " \-\-ignore\-garbage
Ignore non\-alphabet characters when decoding (newlines, spaces, etc).
.TP
.BR \-l ", " \-\-level=\fINUM\fR
Set compression level (1\-19, default 9). Higher values provide better
compression but use more CPU time.
.TP
.BR \-T ", " \-\-threads=\fINUM\fR
Number of compression threads (default 0 = auto). More threads speed up
compression of large files.
.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-verbose
Show compression statistics (bytes in/out, compression ratio).
.TP
.BR \-\-version
Output version information and exit.
.TP
.BR \-\-help
Display help message and exit.
.SH EXAMPLES
Compress and encode a file:
.RS
$ zbase32 document.pdf > document.zb32
.RE
.PP
Decode and decompress:
.RS
$ zbase32 \-d document.zb32 > document.pdf
.RE
.PP
Use in filenames (case\-insensitive safe):
.RS
$ zbase32 secret.key | tee $(zbase32 \-\-wrap=0 <<< "key").zb32
.RE
.SH PERFORMANCE
Base32 encoding adds 60% size overhead (5 bytes â†’ 8 chars). However,
Zstandard compression typically achieves 2\-3x compression on text files,
making the final size competitive with plain Base64.
.PP
Base32 is ideal when case\-insensitive safety is required (DNS, Windows
filesystems, legacy systems).
